const a = [
  {"id":20199,"text":"Which of the following muscles shows a positive Trendelenburg sign when paralyzed?","explanation":"The **Trendelenburg sign** is a clinical test used to assess the strength of the hip abductor muscles, particularly the gluteus medius. When the **gluteus medius** is weak or paralyzed, it fails to stabilize the pelvis during the single-leg stance. As a result, the opposite side of the pelvis drops or tilts downward when the person stands on the affected leg.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe gluteus maximus is not primarily involved in hip abduction; it is more associated with hip extension.\r\n\r\nThe tensor fascia lata is involved in hip abduction, but it is not the primary muscle assessed in the Trendelenburg sign.\r\n\r\nThe piriformis is a lateral rotator of the hip and is not directly assessed in the Trendelenburg sign.\r\n\r\nThe quadratus femoris is a lateral rotator of the hip and is not primarily involved in hip abduction.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 740-741.","responses":[{"text":"Gluteus medius","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Gluteus maximus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tensor fascia lata","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Quadratus femoris","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Piriformis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20200,"text":"During mastectomy and axillary node removal, the surgeon observes a lateral thoracic vein encircling a group of axillary nodes. Which group of nodes are observed?","explanation":"The **pectoral nodes** are a subset of axillary lymph nodes located along the **lateral thoracic vein**. They are situated along the lateral border of the pectoralis minor muscle. During mastectomy and axillary node removal, these nodes may be encountered, especially when addressing the axillary lymphatic drainage.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe central nodes are located in the central part of the axilla and receive lymphatic drainage from other axillary nodes.\r\n\r\nThe posterior nodes are positioned along the subscapular vessels at the posterior axillary fold.\r\n\r\nWhile lateral nodes could be a general term, the lateral thoracic vein's specific reference makes the answer more likely to be related to pectoral nodes.\r\n\r\nThe apical nodes, also known as the subclavicular or apical axillary nodes, are located near the apical (top) part of the axilla.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 188.","responses":[{"text":"Central","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lateral","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Apical","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pectoral","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Posterior","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20317,"text":"A tennis player presents with complaints of pain while at rest at night, especially when lying on the affected shoulder, and weakness while lifting or rotating the arm. The physician diagnoses it as an injury in the shoulder region and predicts the involvement of four muscles. What is the most probable diagnosis?","explanation":"A **rotator cuff tear** involves the tearing of one or more of the tendons of the rotator cuff muscles in the shoulder. The rotator cuff is composed of four muscles: supraspinatus, infraspinatus, teres minor, and subscapularis. These muscles and their tendons play a crucial role in shoulder stability and movement.\r\n\r\nSymptoms of a rotator cuff tear often include pain, particularly at night and during specific movements, as well as weakness in the affected shoulder. The pain may be exacerbated when lying on the affected side.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nInflammation of the bursa in the shoulder can cause pain, but it may not necessarily involve weakness.\r\n\r\nWhile frozen shoulder (adhesive capsulitis) can cause pain and stiffness, it is not associated with a pathology of the four rotator cuff muscles.\r\n\r\nTendinopathy can cause pain and weakness, but the night pain is less characteristic compared to rotator cuff tears. Additionally, tendinopathy usually involves inflammation of a single tendon, not necessarily the four muscles of the rotator cuff.\r\n\r\nAcromioclavicular joint injury is less likely due to the lack of symptoms associated with this condition, such as tenderness over the acromioclavicular joint and pain with specific movements such as reaching across the body.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 174-175.","responses":[{"text":"Frozen shoulder","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rotator cuff tear","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Bursitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tendinopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acromioclavicular joint injury","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20319,"text":"A 26-year-old male is brought to the emergency department with complaints of numbness in the medial three toes of his left foot. He is diagnosed with tarsal tunnel syndrome. Which of the following nerves is most likely involved in this case?","explanation":"**Tarsal tunnel syndrome** is a condition where the **tibial nerve** is compressed or entrapped as it passes through the tarsal tunnel, located on the inner side of the ankle beneath the flexor retinaculum. This compression can lead to symptoms such as numbness, tingling, or pain in the sole of the foot and the toes it innervates.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe femoral nerve primarily supplies the anterior compartment of the thigh.\r\n\r\nThe superficial peroneal nerve supplies the lateral aspect of the leg and the dorsum of the foot. It is not responsible for the medial three toes.\r\n\r\nThe deep peroneal nerve innervates the muscles of the anterior compartment of the leg and the skin between the first and second toes. It is not associated with the symptoms described.\r\n\r\nThe common peroneal nerve divides into the deep and superficial peroneal nerves but is not directly associated with the medial three toes.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 825.","responses":[{"text":"Superficial peroneal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tibial","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Deep peroneal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Femoral","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Common peroneal","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20320,"text":"During limb surgery, ligating the posterior tibial artery at its origin would result in absent blood flow in which artery?","explanation":"When ligating the **posterior tibial artery** at its origin, the blood flow to its branches, including the **lateral plantar artery**, would be compromised.\r\n\r\nThe posterior tibial artery is a major branch of the popliteal artery and provides blood supply to the posterior compartment of the leg. It gives rise to the lateral and medial plantar arteries, which contribute to the arterial supply of the foot.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe anterior tibial artery is a separate branch of the popliteal artery and is not directly affected by ligating the posterior tibial artery.\r\n\r\nThe dorsalis pedis artery is a continuation of the anterior tibial artery and is not affected by ligating the posterior tibial artery.\r\n\r\nThe profunda femoris and descending genicular artery are branches of the femoral artery.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 761.","responses":[{"text":"Descending genicular","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Profunda femoris","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior tibial","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dorsalis pedis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lateral plantar","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":20431,"text":"An infantry army officer develops painful flat feet after several years of service including hundreds of miles of marches. The pain is more on the medial aspect of the sole. Which of the following structures is most likely strained in this condition?","explanation":"**Flat feet**, or pes planus, can result from various causes, and strain on the supporting ligaments and structures of the foot may contribute to the pain.\r\n\r\nThe **plantar calcaneonavicular ligament** supports the head of the talus and helps maintain the longitudinal arch of the foot. Strain or weakness in this ligament can contribute to the development of flat feet, leading to pain on the **medial side**.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe deltoid ligament is located in the ankle and primarily provides stability to the medial side of the ankle joint.\r\n\r\nThe plantar calcaneocuboid ligament supports the lateral longitudinal arch of the foot. Therefore, it is less likely to cause medial pain.\r\n\r\nThe extensor retinaculum is associated with the dorsal aspect of the foot and is not typically related to pain on the medial sole.\r\n\r\nThe calcaneal (Achilles) tendon is located posteriorly and is not directly associated with flat feet.","reference":"Standring S, ed. Gray’s Anatomy: The Anatomical Basis of Clinical Practice. 41st ed. Elsevier Limited; 2016: 1412.","responses":[{"text":"Plantar calcaneonavicular (spring) ligament","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Extensor retinaculum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcaneal (Achilles) tendon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Deltoid ligament","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plantar calcaneocuboid (long plantar) ligament","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20537,"text":"A 50-year-old woman is referred to a general surgeon by her general physician due to a painless swelling on the inside of her upper thigh. During the examination, a herniation is found below and lateral to the pubic tubercle. Where is the herniation most likely to be?","explanation":"The **femoral canal** is a passage located below and **lateral to the pubic tubercle**. It is part of the inguinal region and allows structures such as the femoral vein and lymphatic vessels, to pass between the abdomen and the leg. A herniation or protrusion through the femoral canal can result in a femoral hernia.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe femoral vein is a structure that passes through the femoral canal. Herniation in this area could involve the femoral vein, but the more accurate term for the location of the herniation is the femoral canal.\r\n\r\nThe femoral sheath is a structure that surrounds the femoral vessels and is part of the femoral canal. However, the term \"herniation\" typically refers to a protrusion through a canal rather than the involvement of the sheath itself.\r\n\r\nThe superficial inguinal canal is more medial and is not associated with structures below and lateral to the pubic tubercle.\r\n\r\nThe deep inguinal canal is not a commonly used term. The structures relevant to inguinal hernias are usually discussed in terms of the superficial and deep inguinal rings. The deep inguinal ring is an opening in the transversalis fascia.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 720.","responses":[{"text":"Femoral sheath","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Femoral vein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Femoral canal","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Superficial inguinal canal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Deep inguinal canal","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20539,"text":"What muscle originates from the upper eight ribs, inserts into the medial border and inferior angle of the scapula, and is supplied by the long thoracic nerve?","explanation":"The **serratus anterior** is a muscle located on the lateral aspect of the thorax. It originates from the **upper eight ribs** and inserts into the medial border and inferior angle of the **scapula**. This muscle is crucial for the stabilization and protraction (forward movement) of the scapula.\r\n\r\nThe **long thoracic nerve** (from the roots of C5, C6, and C7) innervates the serratus anterior. Damage to the long thoracic nerve can result in a condition known as winged scapula, where the medial border of the scapula protrudes from the back due to the loss of serratus anterior function.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe subclavius muscle originates from the first rib and inserts into the clavicle.\r\n\r\nThe pectoralis major muscle is supplied by the pectoral nerves.\r\n\r\nThe levator scapulae muscle originates from the upper cervical vertebrae and elevates the scapula. It is innervated by the dorsal scapular nerve.\r\n\r\nThe pectoralis minor muscle originates from the third to fifth ribs and inserts into the coracoid process of the scapula. It is innervated by the medial pectoral nerve.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 168.","responses":[{"text":"Pectoralis minor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Levator scapulae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pectoralis major","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Subclavius","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Serratus anterior","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":20545,"text":"The coracobrachialis muscle originates from the coracoid process of the scapula and attaches to the medial aspect of the shaft of the humerus. Which of the following movements of the arm is assisted by coracobrachialis?","explanation":"The **coracobrachialis muscle** is one of the muscles located in the anterior compartment of the arm. It originates from the coracoid process of the scapula and inserts into the medial aspect of the shaft of the humerus.\r\n\r\nThe primary action of the coracobrachialis muscle is arm **flexion** at the shoulder joint. It assists in bringing the arm forward and medially across the body. While it can contribute to flexion, its role in other movements is limited.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nExtension of the arm is primarily carried out by the triceps brachii, which is located in the posterior compartment of the arm.\r\n\r\nSupination of the forearm supination involves the supinator and biceps brachii.\r\n\r\nThe deltoid muscle, particularly its middle fibers, is the primary muscle responsible for arm abduction. \r\n\r\nMuscles involved in the rotation of the arm at the shoulder joint include the subscapularis (medial rotation), and the infraspinatus and teres minor (lateral rotation).","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 203.","responses":[{"text":"Supination","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Extension","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Abduction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rotation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Flexion","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":20568,"text":"A 35-year-old female housemaid comes to the outpatient department with right knee pain. It began abruptly a few weeks earlier and improved only minimally with NSAIDs. The patient spends hours on her knee while working. Examination reveals no visible erythema or abrasions, but palpation reveals intense localized pain. Although the patient's range of motion is normal, she experienced severe pain while climbing stairs. Which of the following bursae is most likely affected?","explanation":"The prepatellar bursa is located anterior to the patella, between the skin and the patella itself. It serves to reduce friction and allow smooth movement of the patella over the underlying structures during knee flexion and extension. Inflammation of this bursa is known as **prepatellar bursitis** or \"housemaid's knee.\"\r\n\r\nThe patient, who spends **prolonged periods on her knees** as a housemaid, is at risk of repetitive trauma and pressure on the prepatellar bursa. The abrupt onset of right knee pain, localized tenderness on palpation, and aggravation of pain during activities like climbing stairs are consistent with prepatellar bursitis.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe suprapatellar bursa is located above the kneecap and is less exposed to direct pressure from kneeling. It would not explain the specific pain associated with climbing stairs.\r\n\r\nThe anserine bursa, situated on the medial aspect of the knee, can cause pain with inflammation (anserine bursitis), but it is less likely to be associated with the described pattern of pain during knee flexion.\r\n\r\nThe popliteal bursa is situated deep within the knee joint and is less likely to be directly involved in kneeling.\r\n\r\nThe gastrocnemius bursa is located behind the knee. It would not typically cause isolated pain without affecting overall knee movement.","reference":"Sato M, Watari T. Housemaid’s Knee (Prepatellar septic bursitis). Cureus. Accessed October 22, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7549991/","responses":[{"text":"Gastrocnemius","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Suprapatellar","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prepatellar","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Popliteal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anserine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20577,"text":"A male patient came to the hospital complaining of difficulty while walking and experiencing pain in his right thigh. Upon examination, it was observed that he had a weakness in hip flexion and knee extension. However, extension, abduction, and adduction of the hip were all fine, and so was the knee flexion. Based on these symptoms, which muscle is most likely to be injured in this patient?","explanation":"The **rectus femoris** is one of the quadriceps muscles responsible for **knee extension** and is also involved in **hip flexion**. It is innervated by the femoral nerve (L2-L4). Weakness in hip flexion and knee extension, while other hip movements remain intact, suggests an issue with the femoral nerve or the rectus femoris muscle.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe sartorius muscle is involved in hip flexion, abduction, and external rotation.\r\n\r\nThe pectineus muscle, innervated by the femoral and obturator nerves, assists in hip flexion and adduction.\r\n\r\nThe psoas major is a hip flexor but is not involved in knee extension.\r\n\r\nThe obturator internus muscle is a lateral rotator of the hip and is not a primary muscle for hip flexion or knee extension.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 706.","responses":[{"text":"Pectineus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Psoas muscle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sartorius","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rectus femoris","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Obturator internus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20611,"text":"A patient presented with pain and weakness in their right arm after a motor vehicle accident. Upon examination, his arm was adducted, medially rotated, extended, and pronated. Which of the following injuries may have resulted in this condition?","explanation":"**Erb palsy**, also known as Erb-Duchenne palsy, is a brachial plexus injury that typically occurs during a traumatic event, such as a motor vehicle accident. The injury involves the **upper trunk** of the brachial plexus, affecting the C5 and C6 roots.\r\n\r\nThe characteristic position seen in Erb palsy is known as the \"waiter's tip position\". The affected muscles leading to the observed posture are enlisted below.\r\n\r\n- Adduction: deltoid and pectoralis major\r\n- Medial rotation: subscapularis and teres major\r\n- Extension at the elbow: biceps brachii and brachialis\r\n- Pronation: pronator teres and pronator quadratus\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nTraction of the lower trunk (C8-T1 roots) primarily affects hand and finger function, not the shoulder and elbow movements as seen in this case.\r\n\r\nA lesion of the proximal ulnar nerve would affect hand intrinsic muscles and finger flexion.\r\n\r\nA lesion in the distal median nerve would cause sensory and motor loss in the palm and fingers.\r\n\r\nA lesion of the long thoracic nerve would mainly affect the serratus anterior muscle, leading to winging of the scapula.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 199-200.","responses":[{"text":"Lesion in distal median nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lesion of long thoracic nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lesion of proximal ulnar nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Traction of lower trunk (C8-T1 roots)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Traction of upper trunk (C5-C6 roots)","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":20613,"text":"The superficial branch of the ulnar nerve and the ulnar artery lie in the fibro-osseous tunnel, the tunnel of Guyon. Compression of the ulnar nerve in the tunnel of Guyon will lead to a loss of sensation in which of the following areas?","explanation":"The **superficial branch** of the **ulnar nerve** provides sensory information from the **palmar surface of the little finger** and the **medial half of the ring finger**. Compression of this nerve at the Guyon tunnel disrupts the transmission of these sensory signals, leading to numbness and loss of sensation in these specific areas.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nWhile the ulnar nerve also supplies some sensation to the dorsal aspect of the hand, particularly the little finger and half of the ring finger, its main sensory distribution lies on the palmar surface. Compression at the Guyon tunnel does not primarily affect dorsal sensation.\r\n\r\nThe ulnar nerve only supplies the palmar surface of the little finger and medial half of the ring finger, not the entire hand or all fingertips.\r\n\r\nThe ulnar nerve serves the medial aspect of the hand, not the lateral aspect or the four lateral fingers.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 262.","responses":[{"text":"Palmar aspect of lateral four fingers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dorsal aspect of medial three and a half digits","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Palmar surface of the little finger and medial half of the ring finger","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Palmar surface of tips of four and a half digits","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dorsal aspect of the little finger and the medial half of the ring finger","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20615,"text":"A 33-year-old pregnant female came to the outpatient department with complaints of tingling and numbness of the right hand with pain and needle sensations, especially in the thumb and index finger. On examination, the fingers of the right hand were also swollen. The consultant diagnosed her with carpal tunnel syndrome. Which of the following nerves is compressed in this condition?","explanation":"**Carpal tunnel syndrome** (CTS) is a condition characterized by compression of the **median nerve** as it passes through the carpal tunnel, a narrow passageway on the palmar side of the wrist.\r\n\r\nThe carpal tunnel is formed by the carpal bones and the transverse carpal ligament. Compression of the median nerve in this tunnel can result in symptoms such as tingling, numbness, and pain, typically affecting the thumb, index finger, middle finger, and part of the ring finger.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe axillary nerve innervates the deltoid muscle and teres minor, which are responsible for movements of the shoulder joint.\r\n\r\nThe radial nerve provides sensation and motor control to the back of the hand and forearm. Its compression does not typically cause numbness and tingling specifically in the thumb and index finger.\r\n\r\nThe ulnar nerve supplies the little finger and half of the ring finger.\r\n\r\nThe musculocutaneous nerve supplies the biceps brachii and brachialis muscles in the arm.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 237.","responses":[{"text":"Axillary nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Radial nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Median nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ulnar nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Musculocutaneous nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20616,"text":"A beggar on the roadside was suffering from wrist drop in his left hand. What is the site of injury?","explanation":"**Wrist drop** is a condition characterized by the inability to extend the wrist and fingers. It often results from radial nerve injury. The radial nerve runs in the **radial groove** of the humerus, which is located on the posterior aspect of the humerus. This groove is susceptible to injury, especially in cases of fractures or trauma to the midshaft of the humerus.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nGuyon tunnel is a space at the wrist through which the ulnar nerve passes. Injury to the ulnar nerve can lead to paresthesias of the small and ring finger (ulnar tunnel syndrome).\r\n\r\nThe carpal tunnel houses the median nerve, which controls finger flexion and sensation, not wrist extension.\r\n\r\nInjury to the wrist joint itself wouldn't necessarily cause isolated wrist drop without affecting other movements of the wrist and hand.\r\n\r\nThe head of the ulna does not house any major nerves related to wrist movement.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 213.","responses":[{"text":"Carpal tunnel","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Wrist joint","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Radial groove of humerus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Guyon tunnel","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Head of ulna","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20617,"text":"Three compartments divide the leg: anterior, posterior, and lateral, separated by intermuscular septa and interosseous membranes. What is the nerve supply to the lateral compartment?","explanation":"The muscles in the **lateral compartment** of the leg include the fibularis longus and fibularis brevis, which are supplied by the **superficial fibular nerve**. These muscles are primarily responsible for eversion of the foot, which is the movement of the sole away from the midline of the body.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe femoral nerve primarily innervates muscles in the anterior compartment of the thigh.\r\n\r\nThe anterior tibial and deep fibular nerves innervate muscles in the anterior compartment of the leg.\r\n\r\nThe posterior tibial nerve innervates muscles in the posterior compartment of the leg.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 755.","responses":[{"text":"Deep fibular","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior tibial","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Femoral","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superficial fibular","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Posterior tibial","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20618,"text":"Regarding the popliteal fossa, which of the following structures is most deeply placed in the popliteal fossa?","explanation":"The **popliteal fossa** is a diamond-shaped space located at the back of the knee joint. It is bound by the muscles and tendons of the thigh and leg and contains several important neurovascular structures, with the **popliteal artery** being the **most deeply placed** structure in the popliteal fossa.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe small saphenous vein and the posterior cutaneous nerve of the thigh are superficially located in the popliteal fossa.\r\n\r\nThe tibial nerve and the common fibular nerve lie in an intermediate position.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 745-746.","responses":[{"text":"Tibial nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Popliteal artery","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Common fibular nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Small saphenous vein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Posterior cutaneous nerve of thigh","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20619,"text":"Which of the following muscles initiates the unlocking of the knee from a locked position?","explanation":"The **popliteus** muscle is a small but crucial muscle located at the back of the knee joint. Its primary function is to **unlock the knee joint** by laterally rotating the femur on the tibia during the initial stages of flexion. This action is particularly important when transitioning from a fully extended (locked) position to a flexed position, as seen during activities like standing up from a sitting position or beginning the swing phase of walking.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe sartorius muscle is involved in flexion at the hip and knee joints.\r\n\r\nThe adductor magnus plays a role in hip adduction and knee extension.\r\n\r\nThe gastrocnemius is a powerful muscle involved in plantar flexion of the foot and knee flexion.\r\n\r\nThe quadriceps femoris muscles are responsible for knee extension and are not directly involved in the unlocking of the knee.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 757.","responses":[{"text":"Gastrocnemius","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adductor magnus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Popliteus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sartorius","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Quadriceps femoris","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20621,"text":"A football player injures his ankle while attempting to tackle the ball, which resulted in a forceful eversion of his foot during play. The doctor diagnosed him with a sprained deltoid ligament. Which bone does not attach to this ligament?","explanation":"The **deltoid ligament** is a robust ligament on the medial side of the ankle, contributing significantly to the stability of the joint. It has both superficial and deep components and forms a triangular or \"delta\" shape. The deltoid ligament is not attached to the cuboid bone.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe deltoid ligament attaches to the medial surface of the talus, securing the ligament to this important tarsal bone.\r\n\r\nThe deltoid ligament has a broad attachment to the medial malleolus, which is the bony prominence on the inner side of the tibia.\r\n\r\nThe deltoid ligament extends its attachment to the sustentaculum tali, a bony projection on the calcaneum (heel bone). This connection enhances the ligament's role in preventing excessive eversion of the foot.\r\n\r\n The deltoid ligament also attaches to the navicular bone, contributing to the overall support and stability of the medial side of the ankle.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 807.","responses":[{"text":"Cuboid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Talus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Navicular","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Medial malleolus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcaneum","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20622,"text":"When a knife injures the superficial peroneal nerve, which muscle will become paralyzed?","explanation":"The **superficial peroneal nerve** innervates the muscles of the lateral compartment of the leg, including the **peroneus longus** and peroneus brevis. The peroneus longus muscle is primarily responsible for plantar flexion and eversion of the foot and would become paralyzed as a result of injury to the superficial peroneal nerve.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nExtensor digitorum brevis, peroneus tertius, extensor digitorum longus, and extensor hallucis longus are all innervated by the deep peroneal nerve.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 752.","responses":[{"text":"Peroneus longus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Extensor digitorum longus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Extensor hallucis longus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Extensor digitorum brevis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Peroneus tertius","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20623,"text":"A 30-year-old man fell from the third floor and landed on his feet in the parking area of his apartment. Radiographs revealed a fracture of the sustentaculum tali. Which muscle passing immediately beneath it would be adversely affected?","explanation":"The **sustentaculum tali** is a bony shelf on the medial aspect of the calcaneus that provides support for the head of the talus. It also houses a groove on its inferior surface through which the tendon of the **flexor hallucis longus** passes. A fracture of the sustentaculum tali, especially a displaced fracture, can potentially compress or damage the FHL tendon as it runs through the groove. This can lead to weakening and potential tears in the tendon, affecting its ability to flex the great toe.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nTibialis posterior has its tendon located posterior to the sustentaculum tali and is less likely to be directly affected by its fracture.\r\n\r\nPeroneus longus and peroneus tertius lie on the lateral side of the ankle and their tendons do not run directly over the sustentaculum tali.\r\n\r\nTibialis anterior originates on the proximal tibia and fibula and inserts on the foot, passing above the sustentaculum tali and is unlikely to be impacted by its fracture.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 760.","responses":[{"text":"Peroneus longus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tibialis posterior","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tibialis anterior","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Flexor hallucis longus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Peroneus tertius","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20626,"text":"Which of the following muscles in the medial thigh can avoid injury if the main nerve of the compartment is damaged?","explanation":"The muscles of the medial compartment of the thigh are innervated by the obturator nerve. However, the **pectineus** receives additional innervation from the femoral nerve, specifically its medial branch. This **dual innervation** provides some redundancy, meaning that even if the obturator nerve is damaged, the femoral nerve branch can potentially maintain some level of function in the pectineus muscle.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe obturator nerve primarily innervates the adductor longus, adductor brevis, gracilis, and obturator externus. Damage to this nerve would lead to paralysis and loss of function in these muscles.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 707.","responses":[{"text":"Obturator externus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adductor longus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gracilis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pectineus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Adductor brevis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20651,"text":"An athlete injured his long planter ligament while playing leading to pain around his medial longitudinal arch. Which bone forms the summit of the arch?","explanation":"The **medial longitudinal arch** is primarily composed of the talus, navicular, three cuneiforms, and the first three metatarsals. The **talus** sits atop the calcaneus and articulates with the navicular at the talonavicular joint. This articulation plays a crucial role in determining the height and shape of the arch. The head of the talus projects upwards, forming the highest point of the arch, also known as the **summit**.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe navicular is located just anterior to the talus, the navicular supports the head of the talus and forms a key connection within the arch.\r\n\r\nThe calcaneum forms the heel and the posterior pillar of the arch, but it doesn't reach the summit.\r\n\r\nThe medial cuneiform sits within the arch and contributes to its stability.\r\n\r\nThe cuboid bone forms part of the lateral longitudinal arch, not the medial arch.","reference":"Babu D, Bordoni B. Anatomy, bony pelvis and lower limb: medial longitudinal arch of the foot. StatPearls. Published 2023. Accessed October 25, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK562289/","responses":[{"text":"Talus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cuboid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Navicular","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Medial cuneiform","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcaneum","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20653,"text":"An orthopedic surgeon is performing arthroscopy of the knee joint of a 30-year-old basketball player. He notices a damaged ligament that is attached to the medial wall of the lateral femoral condyle and inserted into the intercondylar eminence of the tibia. Which of the following intracapsular ligaments is he observing?","explanation":"The **anterior cruciate ligament** (ACL) is a crucial intracapsular ligament in the knee joint. It originates from the medial aspect of the **lateral femoral condyle** and inserts into the **intercondylar eminence** of the tibia. Its primary function is to provide stability to the knee joint, especially during activities that involve sudden stops or changes in direction, as commonly encountered in sports like basketball.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe lateral collateral ligament (LCL) originates from the lateral epicondyle of the femur and inserts into the head of the fibula.\r\n\r\nThe patellar ligament is a continuation of the quadriceps tendon and inserts into the tibial tuberosity.\r\n\r\nThe medial collateral ligament (MCL) originates from the medial epicondyle of the femur and inserts into the medial aspect of the tibia.\r\n\r\nThe posterior cruciate ligament (PCL) originates from the posterior intercondylar area of the femur and inserts into the medial femoral condyle.","reference":"Standring S, ed. Gray’s Anatomy: The Anatomical Basis of Clinical Practice. 41st ed. Elsevier Limited; 2016: 1391.","responses":[{"text":"Anterior cruciate ligament","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Medial collateral ligament","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Patellar","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lateral collateral ligament","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Posterior cruciate ligament","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20753,"text":"A 50-year-old female presented to the neurological outpatient department with complaints of hand numbness, which was diagnosed as carpal tunnel syndrome. Which area of the hand is spared in this condition?","explanation":"**Carpal tunnel syndrome** primarily affects the median nerve while the thenar eminence is innervated by the recurrent branch of the median nerve, which bypasses the carpal tunnel. The sensory loss generally **spares** the dorsum of the hand and the **thenar eminence**.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nCarpal tunnel syndrome usually affects the palmar surface of the thumb, index finger, middle finger, and the radial half of the ring finger, which are all supplied by the median nerve.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 260.","responses":[{"text":"Palmar surface of thumb","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Skin over thenar eminence","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Palmar surface of middle finger","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Palmar surface of index finger","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nail bed of index finger","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20754,"text":"Which of the following carpometacarpal joints allow adequate adduction and abduction in addition to flexion and extension?","explanation":"The **first carpometacarpal (CMC) joint** or the CMC joint of the thumb is a saddle joint. It allows a wide range of movements including flexion, extension, adduction, abduction, and opposition.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe second, third, fourth, and fifth CMC joints are plane synovial joints. They are not designed for significant adduction or abduction, mainly allowing flexion and extension.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 280.","responses":[{"text":"Forth","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Third","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Second","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fifth","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"First","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":20755,"text":"Which of the following bones does not take part in the formation of the wrist joint?","explanation":"The **ulna** is one of the two bones in the forearm. It is located medial to the radius in the supine forearm and is **not directly part of the wrist joint**. It plays a role in the elbow joint, forming a hinge joint with the humerus.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe radius is one of the two forearm bones and plays a crucial role in the formation of the wrist joint. It articulates with the scaphoid and lunate, contributing to the joint's stability and flexibility.\r\n\r\nThe scaphoid, lunate, and triquetral are part of the proximal row of carpal bones and directly contribute to the wrist joint's structure. They articulate with each other and with the radius to facilitate the various movements of the hand.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 278.","responses":[{"text":"Ulna","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Triquetral","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lunate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Radius","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Scaphoid","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20757,"text":"Which of the following muscles contract simultaneously to cause adduction at the wrist joint?","explanation":"**Adduction** at the **wrist** is primarily achieved by the coordinated contraction of flexor carpi ulnaris and extensor carpi ulnaris, which work together to bring the hand toward the midline of the body.\r\n\r\n**Flexor carpi ulnaris** is a powerful flexor and **adductor of the wrist**. It originates from the medial epicondyle of the humerus and the posterior border of the ulna, and inserts into the pisiform, hamate, and base of the fifth metacarpal.\r\n\r\n**Extensor carpi ulnaris** originates from the lateral epicondyle of the humerus and the posterior border of the ulna, and inserts into the base of the fifth metacarpal. It contributes to ulnar deviation, working in conjunction with flexor carpi ulnaris to achieve adduction.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 278.","responses":[{"text":"Flexor carpi radialis and extensor carpi radialis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Flexor carpi ulnaris and flexor carpi radialis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Extensor carpi radialis and extensor carpi ulnaris","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Flexor carpi ulnaris and extensor carpi ulnaris","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Flexor carpi radialis and extensor carpi ulnaris","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20759,"text":"Which joint is the superior radio-ulnar joint?","explanation":"The **superior radio-ulnar joint** is typically classified as a **pivot joint**. In this type of joint, the rounded end of one bone (the head of the radius, in this case) rotates within a ring formed by another bone (the radial notch of the ulna). This pivotal movement allows for supination and pronation of the forearm.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nA saddle joint is characterized by two saddle-shaped articulating surfaces, allowing movement in two planes. An example is the carpometacarpal joint of the thumb.\r\n\r\nA plane joint, also known as a gliding joint, involves flat surfaces that glide against each other. Examples include the intercarpal and intertarsal joints.\r\n\r\nIn a ball and socket joint, the rounded head of one bone fits into the concave socket of another. The hip and shoulder joints are examples of ball and socket joints, providing a wide range of motion.\r\n\r\nA hinge joint allows movement primarily in one plane, like a door hinge. The elbow and knee joints are examples of hinge joints, permitting flexion and extension.","reference":"Standring S, ed. Gray’s Anatomy: The Anatomical Basis of Clinical Practice. 41st ed. Elsevier Limited; 2016: 845.","responses":[{"text":"Ball and socket","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pivot","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Plane","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Saddle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hinge","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20762,"text":"Which of the following is an incorrect statement regarding biceps brachii?","explanation":null,"reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 201.","responses":[{"text":"Chief supinator of radioulnar joint","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bicipital aponeurosis forms the roof of cubital fossa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tendon inserted to radial tuberosity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Innervated by the branch of the lateral cord of the brachial plexus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Short head has intracapsular origin","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":20839,"text":"Regarding the microscopic features of muscles, T tubules are extensions of which of the following structures?","explanation":"Transverse tubules or **T tubules** are invaginations of the cell surface membrane or **sarcolemma** that penetrate the interior of the muscle fiber. They play a crucial role in transmitting the action potential from the cell surface to the interior of the muscle fiber, allowing for the synchronized contraction of the entire muscle cell.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe nucleus is the cellular organelle containing genetic material.\r\n\r\nThe sarcoplasmic reticulum is an organelle responsible for storing and releasing calcium ions during muscle contraction.\r\n\r\nThe sarcoplasm is the cytoplasm of a muscle cell.\r\n\r\nThe rough endoplasmic reticulum is involved in protein synthesis and is not directly related to the formation of T tubules in muscle cells.","reference":"Mescher AL, Junqueira LCU. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 16th ed. McGraw-Hill; 2021: 197-198.","responses":[{"text":"Sarcolemma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Rough endoplasmic reticulum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nucleus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sarcoplasmic reticulum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sarcoplasm","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20841,"text":"A student is examining a slide of bone under a light microscope. Which of the following bone cells will he find along the surface of the bone?","explanation":"**Osteoblasts** are responsible for bone formation. They are found on the **surface of the bone** and play a crucial role in synthesizing and secreting the organic matrix of bone tissue, which eventually mineralizes to become bone. Osteoblasts are actively involved in bone growth and repair.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nLymphocytes are a type of white blood cell involved in the immune response. They are not directly associated with bone tissue.\r\n\r\nOsteoclasts are cells responsible for bone resorption, breaking down bone tissue. They are more commonly found in areas where the bone is being remodeled or resorbed.\r\n\r\nChondrocytes are cells found in cartilage tissue, not bone. They are responsible for maintaining the cartilaginous matrix.\r\n\r\nAn osteon is a structural unit of compact bone, consisting of concentric layers of mineralized matrix. It is not a cell but rather a macroscopic feature observed in bone tissue under a microscope.","reference":"Mescher AL, Junqueira LCU. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 16th ed. McGraw-Hill; 2021: 138.","responses":[{"text":"Osteoclast","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Osteoblast","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lymphocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Osteon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chrondrocytes","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20846,"text":"During a demonstration, the structure and growth of long bones were discussed. Long bones grow in length due to which of the following reasons?","explanation":null,"reference":"Mescher AL, Junqueira LCU. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 16th ed. McGraw-Hill; 2021: 134.","responses":[{"text":"Interstitial growth of cartilage tissue","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Appositional deposition of bone growth","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Endochondral deposition of bone tissue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Removal of calcified cartilage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Interstitial growth of bone tissue","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20850,"text":"What is the most likely feature to be observed as a result of failure of apoptosis?","explanation":"Apoptosis is a programmed cell death process that plays a crucial role in normal development by removing unwanted or excess tissues. Apoptosis between developing digits (interdigital apoptosis) is essential for the separation of individual fingers or toes. \r\n**Failure of apoptosis** can result in the digits remaining connected by tissue, leading to **webbed or fused digits**.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nProximo-distal patterning involves the organization of structures along the limb from the proximal (near the body) to the distal (away from the body) regions. It is not dependent on apoptosis.\r\n\r\nApoptosis is not directly associated with the formation of the overlying epidermis.\r\n\r\nApoptosis is more involved in sculpting and shaping structures rather than determining different bone types.\r\n\r\nApoptosis is not the primary factor for the formation of bones and muscles. Other processes, such as cell differentiation and migration, contribute to the development of these structures.","reference":"Sadler TW. Langman’s Medical Embryology. 14th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 167.","responses":[{"text":"All bones would form as the same structure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The digits would be connected by webbing, and would not be separated","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"The proximo-distal patterning would not occur normally","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The bones and muscles would not form","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The overlying epidermis would not form","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20852,"text":"Somites develop from which of the following embryological derivates?","explanation":"During early embryogenesis, **somites** form through a process known as somitogenesis from the **paraxial mesoderm**, which is a region of mesodermal tissue adjacent to the neural tube. These somites give rise to various structures, including skeletal muscles, bones, and connective tissues along the vertebral column.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nNeural crest cells contribute to the development of a variety of structures such as the peripheral nervous system, but they are not the origin of somites.\r\n\r\nThe ectoderm gives rise to the outermost layer of the embryonic germ layers and contributes to the development of the nervous system, epidermis, and other tissues. However, it is not directly involved in somite formation.\r\n\r\nThe lateral plate mesoderm contributes to the formation of the visceral muscles and mesenchyme. It is not the origin of somites.\r\n\r\nThe endoderm gives rise to the innermost layer of the embryonic germ layers, contributing to the formation of the gastrointestinal and respiratory systems. It is not involved in somitogenesis.","reference":"Gilbert SF. Paraxial mesoderm: the somites and their derivatives. Developmental Biology. 6th edition. Published 2000. Accessed October 31, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK10085/","responses":[{"text":"Lateral plate mesoderm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Paraxial mesoderm","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Endoderm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neural crest cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ectoderm","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20853,"text":"The Z disc is made up of which of the following proteins?","explanation":null,"reference":"Knöll R, Buyandelger B, Lab M. The sarcomeric z-disc and z-discopathies. Journal of Biomedicine and Biotechnology. Published 2011. Accessed October 31, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3199094/","responses":[{"text":"Nebulin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Myomesin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Actin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"α-Actinin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"C-protein","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20889,"text":"What is the primary function of titin in skeletal muscles?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 79-81.","responses":[{"text":"Provides elasticity and recoil to muscle fibers after stretching","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stabilizes the myosin filaments","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Acts as an ATPase enzyme","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anchors the actin filaments to the Z-lines","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Facilitates the release of calcium ions from the sarcoplasmic reticulum","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20891,"text":"What is the distance between one actin filament and the next actin filament on the same sarcomere?","explanation":null,"reference":"Mescher AL, Junqueira LCU. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 16th ed. McGraw-Hill; 2021: 199.","responses":[{"text":"Z line","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"H zone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A band","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"M line","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"I band","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20892,"text":"In resting skeletal muscle, what is the optimum length of the sarcomere at which it can contract with maximum force of contraction?","explanation":"The **sarcomere** length at which it can contract with the maximum force of contraction is known as the **optimal length**, which is **2.2 µm**. At this length, there is an optimal overlap of actin and myosin filaments, allowing for the most effective cross-bridge formation and force generation.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 85.","responses":[{"text":"1.8 mm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"2.2 µm","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"2.5 µm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"1.65 µm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"3.0 µm","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20893,"text":"Large amounts of ATP are cleaved to form ADP during the contraction process, and the greater the amount of work performed by the muscle, the greater the amount of ATP that is cleaved. What is the name of this phenomenon?","explanation":"During muscle contraction, the process of converting adenosine triphosphate (ATP) to adenosine diphosphate (ADP) releases energy that fuels the contractile activity of the muscle. The phenomenon where **larger amounts of ATP** are cleaved to form ADP as the muscle performs **more work** is known as the **Fenn effect**.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe cross-bridge theory primarily focuses on the interaction between actin and myosin during muscle contraction. It involves the formation and breaking of cross-bridges between myosin heads and actin filaments.\r\n\r\nThe ratchet theory proposes a molecular ratcheting mechanism in muscle contraction where myosin heads move along actin filaments.\r\n\r\nThe power stroke refers to the movement of myosin heads, leading to the sliding of actin and myosin filaments during muscle contraction.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 84.","responses":[{"text":"Fenn effect","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ratchet theory of contraction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Power stroke","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Actin power-stroke theory","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cross-bridge theory","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20894,"text":"A 28-year-old woman has reported experiencing weakness in the muscles of her face and neck, which has resulted in double vision and difficulty swallowing. Over time, the weakness has also affected her upper and lower limbs. She notes that the muscle weakness becomes more prominent in the evening. The cause of this condition is believed to be antibodies against which of the following?","explanation":"**Myasthenia gravis** is an autoimmune disorder characterized by the production of **antibodies** against the **acetylcholine receptors** (AChR) at the neuromuscular junction. These antibodies interfere with the normal transmission of nerve impulses to muscles, leading to **progressive muscle weakness** and fatigue, often beginning from the muscles of the face and neck. Symptoms of myasthenia gravis typically worsen as the day goes on.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nAcetylcholinesterase (AChE) is responsible for breaking down acetylcholine in the synaptic cleft. Antibodies against AChE would not lead to the described symptoms; instead, they might cause an excess of acetylcholine and prolonged muscle contraction.\r\n\r\nMyasthenia gravis is not associated with antibodies against acetylcholine itself.\r\n\r\nWhile the motor end plate is involved in neuromuscular transmission, antibodies against it are not a characteristic feature of myasthenia gravis.\r\n\r\nAcetylcholine receptors, which are the primary site of pathology in myasthenia gravis,  are located on the postsynaptic membrane, not the presynaptic membrane.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 97.","responses":[{"text":"Acetylcholine receptors","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Acetylcholine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Presynaptic membrane","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acetylcholinesterase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Motor end plate","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20895,"text":"An experiment was conducted to distinguish between the contraction mechanisms of skeletal and smooth muscles. The contractile properties of isolated guinea pig intestine and skeletal muscles were studied following stimulation. The key difference between the two muscle types is that skeletal muscle contraction requires, but smooth muscle contraction does not require, which of the following?","explanation":"When calcium ions are released from the sarcoplasmic reticulum in **skeletal muscle** response to an action potential, these calcium ions bind to troponin. This binding induces a conformational change in **troponin**, causing it to move tropomyosin away from the myosin-binding sites on the actin filaments. This exposure allows myosin heads to bind to actin, initiating the cross-bridge cycle and leading to muscle contraction.\r\n\r\nOn the other hand, smooth muscle contraction does not rely on troponin.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nIn smooth muscle contraction, calmodulin activates myosin light-chain kinase (MLCK), leading to the phosphorylation of myosin.\r\n\r\nActin and myosin are involved in the contraction of both skeletal and smooth muscle.","reference":"Gash MC, Kandle PF, Murray IV, Varacallo M. Physiology, muscle contraction. StatPearls. Published 2023. Accessed November 1, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537140/","responses":[{"text":"Troponin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Myosin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Myosin light-chain kinase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Actin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calmodulin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20927,"text":"A 5-year-old girl suffering from severe Hurler syndrome presents with corneal clouding, mental retardation, dwarfing, and coarse facial features. Degradation of mucopolysaccharides dermatan sulfate and heparin sulfate are affected. Which enzyme is deficient in this condition?","explanation":"**α-L-iduronidase** is involved in the degradation of mucopolysaccharides. A deficiency of this enzyme is associated with **Hurler syndrome**.\r\n\r\nHurler syndrome, also known as mucopolysaccharidosis type I is an autosomal recessive lysosomal storage disorder. It is characterized by the accumulation of glycosaminoglycans (GAGs), particularly **dermatan sulfate** and **heparan sulfate**, which can result in severe corneal clouding, mental retardation, dwarfism, and coarse facial features.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nHeparan sulfamidase causes Sanfilippo syndrome, a different subtype of mucopolysaccharidosis. Sanfilippo syndrome typically affects the breakdown of heparan sulfate while both heparan sulfate and dermatan sulfate are affected in this case.\r\n\r\nN-acetylglucosamine and iduronate are components of glycosaminoglycans. They are not enzymes.\r\n\r\nDeficiency of β-glucuronidase is associated with Sly syndrome, which affects the breakdown of chondroitin sulfate and glucuronyl glycosphingolipids.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 164.","responses":[{"text":"Heparan sulfamidase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"α-L-Iduronidase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"β-Glucuronidase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"N-Acetylglucosamine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Iduronate sulfate","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20929,"text":"A newborn is brought with multiple fractures with no history of major trauma, kyphosis, and delayed wound healing. Pediatrician suspects disease involving the inability of collagen to form fibers properly leading to bowing or fracture of long bones. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"Multiple fractures with no history of major trauma, kyphosis, and delayed wound healing are features of **osteogenesis imperfecta**. It arises due to genetic mutations that lead to impairment in the production or processing of **collagen**, resulting in weak and brittle bones.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nOsteoporosis is characterized by decreased bone density but is not typically associated with fractures in newborns. It is more common in the elderly population.\r\n\r\nOsteomalacia refers to the softening of the bones due to vitamin D deficiency, not impaired synthesis of collagen fibers.\r\n\r\nPaget disease is characterized by abnormal bone remodeling, leading to enlarged and deformed bones, but it is not typically associated with fractures in a newborn.\r\n\r\nRickets is a disorder caused by a deficiency of vitamin D, calcium, or phosphate, leading to impaired mineralization of growing bone. However, it is not associated with impaired collagen synthesis.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 49.","responses":[{"text":"Osteomalacia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Osteogenesis imperfecta","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Osteoporosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rickets","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Paget disease","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20931,"text":"Which enzyme is responsible for the strength, stability, and cross-linking of collagen fibers?","explanation":"**Lysyl oxidase** plays a crucial role in collagen formation by catalyzing the covalent cross-linking of lysine and hydroxylysine residues within collagen molecules. This **cross-linking** contributes to the structural integrity and tensile strength of collagen fibers.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nHyaluronidase is an enzyme that hydrolyzes hyaluronic acid, a component of the extracellular matrix.\r\n\r\nProlyl oxidase hydroxylates proline residues in collagen, contributing to collagen stability but not directly forming cross-links.\r\n\r\nHydroxy collagenase is an enzyme that degrades collagen.\r\n\r\nElastase is an enzyme that degrades elastin.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 48.","responses":[{"text":"Hydroxy collagenase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prolyl oxidase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Elastase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lysyl oxidase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyaluronidase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20932,"text":"Which of the following is a primary storage form of vitamin D?","explanation":"The primary **storage** form of **vitamin D** is 25-hydroxycholecalciferol. This compound is produced in the liver after the initial conversion of cholecalciferol (obtained from the skin or diet) to **25-hydroxycholecalciferol**.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\n7-dehydrocholesterol is the precursor to cholecalciferol in the skin.\r\n\r\nErgocalciferol is a form of vitamin D obtained from plants and yeast. It undergoes similar conversion processes in the liver and kidneys to become biologically active.\r\n\r\n1,25-dihydroxycholecalciferol is the biologically active form of vitamin D. It is synthesized in the kidneys from 25-hydroxycholecalciferol and is essential for regulating calcium and phosphate metabolism.\r\n\r\nCholecalciferol is a precursor to 25-hydroxycholecalciferol and is derived from animal sources or synthesized in the skin in response to sunlight exposure.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 390.","responses":[{"text":"Cholecalciferol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"7-dehydrocholestrol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"1,25-dihydroxycholecalciferol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"25-hydroxycholecalciferol","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ergocalciferol","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20936,"text":"Which of the following hormones is responsible for inhibiting the resorption of bones by osteoclasts, reducing mobilization of calcium and inorganic PO4 from bones into the blood?","explanation":"**Calcitonin** opposes the actions of parathyroid hormone (PTH). It downregulates osteoclast activity, leading to decreased breakdown of bone tissue. This results in a decrease in the release of calcium and phosphate from the bones into the blood.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nTestosterone primarily stimulates bones bone formation. It does not directly inhibit bone resorption.\r\n\r\nInsulin primarily regulates glucose metabolism and has minor effects on bone metabolism. It can indirectly promote bone formation but does not significantly inhibit resorption.\r\n\r\nParathyroid hormone promotes bone resorption to raise calcium levels in the blood.\r\n\r\nThyroxine plays a role in bone metabolism, mainly during development and growth. It can stimulate bone formation and resorption to some extent, but its effect on resorption is less pronounced than that of calcitonin.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 391.","responses":[{"text":"Insulin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Testosterone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcitonin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Parathyroid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thyroxine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20940,"text":"Which of the following is the least likely feature of osteoporosis?","explanation":"**Bone mass between 1-2.5 standard deviations (SD) below the mean peak bone mass** is a characteristic feature of **osteopenia**, the precursor to osteoporosis. Both osteoporosis and osteopenia are characterized by a decrease in bone density and mass, leading to bone fragility and an increased risk of fractures. However, for diagnosis of osteoporosis, the bone mass should be lower than 2.5 SD below the mean peak bone mass.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nNon-traumatic fractures are a hallmark feature of osteoporosis. \r\n\r\nEstrogen decline after menopause is a major risk factor for osteoporosis in women.\r\n\r\nSenile changes, or the general physiological decline associated with aging, can contribute to bone loss.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1187.","responses":[{"text":"Bone mass is 1-2.5 SD below the mean peak bone mass","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Severe osteopenia that significantly increases the risk of fracture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Common due to senile changes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Common after menopause","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Presence of non-traumatic fracture","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20943,"text":"Osteomyelitis denotes inflammation of bone and marrow, virtually always secondary to infections. What is the most common organism causing osteomyelitis in sickle cell anemia patients?","explanation":"Individuals with sickle cell anemia are more susceptible to infections such as osteomyelitis due to impaired splenic function. ***Salmonella*** is a gram-negative bacillus that most commonly causes **osteomyelitis** in individuals with **sickle cell anemia**. Common symptoms of osteomyelitis include localized pain, swelling, redness, and tenderness over the affected bone.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nGroup B streptococci are less commonly associated with osteomyelitis, although they can cause osteomyelitis in neonates and infants with sickle cell disease.\r\n\r\n*Haemophilus influenzae* is rarely implicated in cases of osteomyelitis.\r\n\r\n*Escherichia coli* is not a typical causative organism for osteomyelitis in sickle cell anemia patients.\r\n\r\nMixed bacterial infections are not as common as single-organism cases in sickle cell anemia-related osteomyelitis.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1195.","responses":[{"text":"Escherichia coli","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mixed bacterial infections","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Haemophilus influenzae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Salmonella","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Group B streptococci","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20959,"text":"A 28-year-old male flips over an all-terrain vehicle and lands on his leg. On physical examination, there is intense palpation over the right shin but no shortening of the limb. The overlying skin is intact. A radiograph shows a right tibial and fibular midshaft fracture into multiple bone fragments. Which of the following terms best describes these fractures?","explanation":"**Comminuted fractures** occur when a bone is shattered into **multiple fragments**, and this often happens due to high-energy trauma or significant force applied to the bone. In this case, the midshaft fractures of both the tibia and fibula into multiple fragments indicate a severe and fragmented break.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nDisplaced fractures involve a separation of bone fragments, leading to a misalignment. However, in the scenario, no limb shortening is mentioned, suggesting that the fragments may still be relatively in alignment.\r\n\r\nCompound fractures are characterized by a break in the bone that pierces through the skin. Since the overlying skin is described as intact in this case, the fractures are not compound.\r\n\r\nPathological fractures occur in bones weakened by underlying diseases, such as tumors or metabolic conditions but there is no history of an underlying disease in this case.\r\n\r\nIncomplete fractures involve a partial break in the bone. The description of the fractures as breaking into multiple bone fragments indicates a more severe injury that is consistent with a comminuted fracture.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1193.","responses":[{"text":"Compound","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Incomplete","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pathological","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Comminuted","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Displaced","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20960,"text":"A 55-year-old male with a history of pain and loss of sensation in his lower extremities, repeated trauma, and deformed joints presented to the outpatient department. Biopsy from gummatous lesion shows fibrinoid necrosis characterized by edematous granulation tissue containing numerous plasma cells and necrotic bone. What is the most probable diagnosis?","explanation":"Fibrinoid necrosis, edematous granulation tissue with numerous plasma cells, and necrotic bone are classic indicators of **syphilitic osteomyelitis**, which is caused by ***Treponema pallidum***. This diagnosis is further supported by the patient's history of pain, loss of sensation in the lower extremities, repeated trauma, and deformed joints.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nOsteomyelitis caused by *Salmonella* typically lacks the distinct fibrinoid necrosis seen in syphilitic osteomyelitis.\r\n\r\nOsteomalacia due to vitamin D deficiency involves bone softening and increased risk of fractures. It is not associated with gummatous lesions or neurologic symptoms such as loss of sensation.\r\n\r\nAge-related bone loss can increase fracture risk, but it is not associated with gummatous lesions, neurological symptoms, or fibroid necrosis.\r\n\r\n*Escherichia coli* is a relatively less common cause of osteomyelitis and is not associated with neurological symptoms seen in this case.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1196.","responses":[{"text":"Infection by salmonella","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"E. coli causing osteomyelitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased tendency of fracture due to age","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Infection by Treponema pallidum","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Osteomalacia due to vitamin D deficiency","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20969,"text":"Why is aspirin considered unique among non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs?","explanation":"**Aspirin irreversibly** acetylates and **inactivates cyclooxygenase** (COX), inhibiting the synthesis of prostaglandins and thromboxane A₂. This unique irreversible inhibition distinguishes aspirin from other NSAIDs, which typically exert their effects through reversible inhibition of COX.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nAspirin is non-selective and inhibits both COX-1 and COX-2 enzymes.\r\n\r\nAspirin has antipyretic effects through its action on COX, but this is not unique to aspirin among NSAIDs.\r\n\r\n There is no evidence to suggest that aspirin increases the risk of colon cancer. In fact, long-term aspirin use has been associated with a decreased risk of colorectal cancer.\r\n\r\nWhile aspirin has anti-inflammatory properties, it is not commonly used for the prevention of gouty arthritis since it can interfere with the excretion of uric acid.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 512.","responses":[{"text":"Decreases fever","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prevents episodes of gouty arthritis with long term use","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It selectively inhibits cyclooxygenase enzyme","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Irreversibly inhibits its target enzyme","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Increases the risk of colon cancer","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20971,"text":"Which of the following drugs is analgesic and antipyretic but weak as an anti-inflammatory drug?","explanation":"**Acetaminophen** is known for its analgesic and antipyretic properties. However, it has **limited anti-inflammatory** effects compared to other nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs).\r\n\r\nAcetaminophen works by inhibiting prostaglandin synthesis in the central nervous system, which helps reduce fever and alleviate pain. It is often considered a first-line option for individuals who cannot tolerate the potential gastrointestinal side effects associated with NSAIDs.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nIndomethacin is a potent NSAID with marked anti-inflammatory, analgesic, and antipyretic effects.\r\n\r\nProbenecid is primarily used in the treatment of gout by increasing uric acid excretion. It lacks significant analgesic or antipyretic properties.\r\n\r\nCelecoxib is a selective COX-2 inhibitor, belonging to the NSAID class. It possesses analgesic, antipyretic, and anti-inflammatory effects.\r\n\r\nColchicine is utilized in the treatment of gout and familial Mediterranean fever, primarily for its anti-inflammatory properties, but it is not a prominent analgesic or antipyretic.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 513.","responses":[{"text":"Celecoxib","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acetaminophen","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Indomethacin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Colchicine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Probenecid","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20972,"text":"The chronic use of aspirin as an analgesic may result in which of the following adverse effects?","explanation":"**Aspirin** is a nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drug (NSAID) that inhibits cyclooxygenase (COX) enzymes, leading to a reduction in prostaglandin synthesis. Prostaglandins play a protective role in the gastrointestinal mucosa, and their inhibition by long-term aspirin use can contribute to the development of **gastric ulcers**.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nHeart failure, headaches, gout, and vertigo are not prominent adverse effects of aspirin.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 514.","responses":[{"text":"Headache","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vertigo","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gout","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Heart failure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastric ulcer","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":20981,"text":"Which of the following is the primary cause of death from acetaminophen overdose?","explanation":"**Acetaminophen** is metabolized in the liver through two main pathways; glucuronidation, which produces a nontoxic metabolite, and sulfation. However, when these pathways become saturated due to an overdose, a significant portion of acetaminophen is metabolized via the cytochrome P450 system, specifically the CYP2E1 enzyme. This alternative pathway leads to the production of a highly toxic metabolite, N-acetyl-p-benzoquinone imine (NAPQI).\r\n\r\nNAPQI, if not effectively detoxified by glutathione, forms adducts with hepatic proteins, resulting in widespread hepatocellular necrosis. This process ultimately leads to **liver failure**, a potentially fatal consequence of acetaminophen overdose.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nAcetaminophen toxicity primarily affects the liver, not the kidneys.\r\n\r\nStatus asthmaticus, A-V conduction disturbance, and status epilepticus are not typically associated with acetaminophen overdose.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 517.","responses":[{"text":"Liver failure","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Status epilepticus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A-V conduction disturbance","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute nephropathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Status asthmaticus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20982,"text":"Aspirin effect on blood clotting involves which of the following mechanisms?","explanation":"Thromboxane A₂ promotes platelet activation, adhesion, and aggregation, contributing to the formation of blood clots. **Aspirin inhibits the synthesis of thromboxane A₂**, thereby **reducing** the activation and **aggregation of platelets**, thereby inhibiting the early stages of blood clot formation. This antiplatelet effect is particularly valuable in the prevention of cardiovascular events such as myocardial infarction and stroke.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nWhile ADP also promotes platelet aggregation, it works downstream of the thromboxane A₂ pathway. The primary action of aspirin is on thromboxane A2 synthesis, not directly on ADP receptors.\r\n\r\nAntithrombin III is activated by anticoagulants such as heparin.\r\n\r\nThe inhibition of vitamin K-dependent clotting factor synthesis in the liver is carried out by warfarin.\r\n\r\nFibrinogen is a protein involved in the later stages of clot formation, and aspirin neither stimulates nor inhibits its synthesis.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 514.","responses":[{"text":"Activating antithrombin III and inhibiting thrombin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blocking platelet receptor for ADP","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibiting hepatic vitamin K dependent clotting factor synthesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stimulate fibrinogenic synthesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Preventing platelet aggregation by inhibiting thromboxane A2 synthesis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21035,"text":"Erikson's theory proposes that each stage of psychosocial development is marked by a conflict or crisis that an individual must resolve. When a stage is not managed well, it can lead to a negative outcome, such as malignancy or maladaptation of behavior. Conversely, if the stage is managed too well, it can result in an overly positive disposition, such as a person who trusts too much. What is the term used to refer to this negative disposition?","explanation":"According to Erikson's theory of psychosocial development, the term \"**ego dystonic**\" is used to refer to a negative disposition arising from the mismanagement of a developmental stage. It describes a condition where one's thoughts, feelings, or behaviors conflict with their ideal self-image.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nVirtue represents a positive trait developed through the successful resolution of a stage, not a negative disposition.\r\n\r\nConflicts and crises are inherent in each stage of development. It is not used to specify a negative or positive outcome.\r\n\r\nTemperature is unrelated to Erikson's psychosocial stages.","reference":"Orenstein GA, Lewis L. Eriksons stages of psychosocial development. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2023. Accessed November 15, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK556096/","responses":[{"text":"Conflict","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Temperature","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Virtue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ego dystonic","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Crisis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21055,"text":"One DALY represents the loss of one year of full health. It is mathematically represented by which one of the following equations?","explanation":"Disability-adjusted life years (DALY) is a metric used to quantify the overall burden of disease, taking into account both premature mortality and the impact of disability. It is given by the following equation:\r\n\r\n**DALY = YLL + YLD** (years of life lost + years lived with disability)\r\n\r\n**Years of life lost** (YLL) represents the years of potential life that are lost due to premature mortality. It is calculated by considering the difference between the life expectancy at the age of death and the actual age at which death occurs.\r\n\r\n**Years lived with disability** (YLD) involves multiplying the duration of time a person lives with a disability by a disability weight, which quantifies the severity of the disability on a scale from 0 (perfect health) to 1 (equivalent to death). The product of these values gives the years of healthy life lost due to disability.","reference":"Park K. Park’s Textbook of Preventive and Social Medicine. 25th ed. Bhanot Publishers; 2019: 26.","responses":[{"text":"DALY = L + YLL (life expectancy at age of death + years of life lost)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"DALY = DW + YLD (disability weight + years lived with disability)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"DALY = DW + YLL (disability weight + years of life lost)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"DALY = YLL + YLD (years of life lost + years lived with disability)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"DALY = YLD + L (years lived with disability+ life expectancy at the age of death)","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21056,"text":"What is the term used to describe the physiological ability of women to give birth to children?","explanation":null,"reference":"Dow Lecture slides: Locomotor, community medicine, topic name: Determinants of fertility and mortality.","responses":[{"text":"Fertility","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Fecundity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"General fertility rate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Total fertility rate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Reproductive life span","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21057,"text":"What is the minimum number of X-ray views required to confidently rule out a scaphoid fracture in most cases?","explanation":"Scaphoid fractures can sometimes be subtle, and obtaining multiple views helps improve the chances of detection. To confidently rule out a **scaphoid fracture** in most cases, **four X-ray views** of the scaphoid series are typically recommended. This series includes a posteroanterior (PA) view, PA view with ulnar deviation, lateral view, and semi-pronated oblique view.","reference":"Dow Lecture slides: Locomotor, radiology, topic name: Radiological anatomy of upper and lower limb x-ray.","responses":[{"text":"Single view is enough","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Two standard X-ray views","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Four X-rays views of scaphoid series","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Five X-rays views of scaphoid series","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Three X-ray views","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21058,"text":"A 30-year-old male patient presented to the emergency department with complaints of pain in his right knee after a fall. Although the x-ray was normal, the ER physician suspects a possible ligament injury. What would be the most appropriate next diagnostic test to confirm the condition?","explanation":"**Magnetic resonance imaging** (MRI) is a highly sensitive imaging modality that provides detailed images of **ligaments**, tendons, and other soft tissues, allowing for a more accurate assessment of injuries that may not be visible on standard X-rays. Since the physician suspects an injury to the ligaments of the right knee, after ruling out the possibility of a fracture through an X-ray, an MRI of the affected knee is the next appropriate step.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\n\r\nWhile computed tomography (CT) scans can also visualize soft tissues to some extent, they are not as detailed as MRIs. Moreover, CT scans involve more radiation exposure than MRIs.\r\n\r\nX-rays are not useful for visualizing soft tissues such as ligaments. Since the initial x-ray is normal and there is a suspicion of ligament injury, additional X-ray views would not be as useful as an MRI.\r\n\r\nContrast-enhanced CT scans are not the first-line imaging modality for ligament injuries. MRI remains the preferred choice for assessing soft tissue structures.","reference":"Dow Lecture slides: Locomotor, radiology, topic name: Cross-sectional anatomy of upper and lower limbs.","responses":[{"text":"MRI of the right knee","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"CT scan of the right knee","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Contrast enhanced CT scan of the right knee","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"X-ray of the right knee with additional views","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of the above","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21059,"text":"A 40-year-old woman came to the emergency department with a sign of foot drop. Which of the following nerves could have been damaged?","explanation":"The **deep peroneal nerve** is a branch of the common peroneal nerve. It innervates the muscles responsible for dorsiflexion of the foot, including the anterior tibialis muscle. Lesions of this nerve can result in the inability to lift the foot upward, leading to **foot drop**.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe posterior tibial nerve is primarily involved in innervating muscles responsible for plantar flexion and inversion of the foot and is not associated with foot drop.\r\n\r\nThe femoral nerve innervates the muscles of the anterior thigh, which are responsible for the extension of the knee and flexion of the hip joint. \r\n\r\nThe superficial peroneal nerve is involved in sensation and motor function for the lateral compartment of the leg.\r\n\r\nThe anterior tibial nerve supplies the muscles responsible for dorsiflexion of the toes and ankle, but it doesn't have a significant impact on lifting the entire foot. Damage to this nerve can cause weakness in toe movement, but not full foot drop.","reference":"Nori SL, Stretanski MF. Foot drop. StatPearls. Published 2023. Accessed November 16, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK554393/","responses":[{"text":"Posterior tibial nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Femoral nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior tibial nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Deep peroneal nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Superficial peroneal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21060,"text":"Which of the following drugs inhibits both cyclooxygenase 1 and 2?","explanation":"**Aspirin** is a nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drug (NSAID) that exerts its effects by irreversibly inhibiting both **cycloxygenase 1 and 2** (COX-1 and COX-2) enzymes, leading to decreased production of prostaglandins. It is mainly used for its antiplatelet properties.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nCelecoxib is a selective COX-2 inhibitor, meaning it specifically targets COX-2 without affecting COX-1.\r\n\r\nAcetaminophen primarily acts centrally in the brain and has weak anti-inflammatory properties. It does not significantly inhibit COX enzymes in peripheral tissues.\r\n\r\nMisoprostol is a prostaglandin analog and is not a direct inhibitor of COX enzymes.\r\n\r\nAllopurinol inhibits the enzyme xanthine oxidase. It is used to treat hyperuricemia.","reference":"Dow Lecture slides: Locomotor, Pharmacology, Topic name: NSAIDS.","responses":[{"text":"Acetaminophen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Allopurinol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aspirin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Celecoxib","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Misoprostol","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21682,"text":"What happens when the apical ridge is removed?","explanation":"The **apical ectodermal ridge** (AER) plays a crucial role in limb development by inducing the formation of the progress zone, which is responsible for generating **distal structures**. Removal of the apical ridge disrupts this signaling, leading to the development of proximal structures only.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nRemoval of the apical ridge does not lead to limb bud degeneration; instead, it alters the pattern of limb development.\r\n\r\nRegeneration of a functional apical ectodermal ridge or limb bud does not occur after the removal.\r\n\r\nThe absence of the apical ridge disrupts the induction of the progress zone, affecting further development.","reference":"(1) Verheyden JM, Sun X. Embryology meets molecular biology: deciphering the apical ectodermal ridge. Developmental biology. Published September 15, 2017. Accessed December 17, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5526742/\r\n\r\n(2) Fernandez-Teran M, Ros MA. The Apical Ectodermal Ridge: morphological aspects and signaling pathways. The International Journal of Developmental Biology.","responses":[{"text":"Regeneration of the entire limb bud from underlying mesoderm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Degeneration of the limb bud","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Regeneration of new apical ridge from adjacent epidermal tissue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Continued development in the progress zone, once the apical ridge has induced progress zone formation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Formation of structures proximal to the apical ridge, but no formation of new distal structures","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21686,"text":"Which of the following factors primarily determines the strength of a muscle contraction?","explanation":"The **size principle** dictates that smaller motor units with lower force-generating capacity are recruited first, followed by larger motor units with greater force capacity. This principle aligns with the idea that the **strength** of a muscle contraction is primarily determined by the **number of muscle fibers** recruited. As the demand for force increases, larger motor units with more muscle fibers are sequentially activated.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nWhile muscle fiber type influences contraction speed and endurance, the peak force generated is dependent on the number of muscle fibers involved.\r\n\r\nAlthough optimal muscle length allows for maximum overlap of actin and myosin filaments, it is not the primary determinant of strength.\r\n\r\nThe presence of acetylcholine receptors is a prerequisite for the initiation of muscle contraction. However, they do not determine the strength of the contraction.\r\n\r\nThe thickness of the sarcolemma does not directly influence the contractile force.","reference":"(1) Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 89, 91.\r\n\r\n(2) Costanzo LS. BRS: Physiology. 5th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2011: 47.","responses":[{"text":"The length of muscle at rest","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The type of muscle fibers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The presence of acetylcholine receptors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The number of muscle fibers recruited","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"The thickness of sarcolemma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21691,"text":"What is the term used to describe a system that records vital events such as births and deaths in a specific area?","explanation":"**Vital registration** refers to the systematic recording of **births** and **deaths** in a specific geographic area. It plays a crucial role in public health and epidemiology by providing essential data for understanding population dynamics and health trends.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nWhile surveillance may involve monitoring health-related events,  it is a broader term that encompasses various types of data collection beyond just births and deaths.\r\n\r\nA demographic sample survey involves collecting data from a subset of the population rather than the entire population. \r\n\r\nService statistics refers to data related to the utilization of a service.\r\n\r\nA population census aims to collect data on the entire population, at a specific point in time, not continuously recording ongoing vital events.","reference":"Jackson D, Wenz K, Muniz M, et al. Civil registration and vital statistics in health systems. Bulletin of the World Health Organization. Published December 1, 2018. Accessed December 18, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6249696/","responses":[{"text":"Vital registration","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Population census","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Demographic sample survey","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Surveillance","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Service statistics","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21692,"text":"During a motorbike accident, a 15-year-old boy lost sensory innervation from the medial side of the leg and foot. Which of the following statements is incorrect regarding the nerve involved?","explanation":"The loss of sensory innervation from the medial side of the leg and foot is consistent with damage to the **saphenous nerve**, which provides sensory innervation to the affected area. The saphenous nerve is **not a mixed nerve**.\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe saphenous nerve is a branch of the femoral nerve.\r\n\r\nThe saphenous nerve descends through the adductor canal.\r\n\r\nThe saphenous nerve is purely sensory and has no motor function.","reference":"Arnold C, Alvarado AC, Brady MF. Saphenous nerve block. StatPearls. Published 2023. Accessed December 18, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK536967/","responses":[{"text":"Branch of femoral nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Content of adductor canal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mixed nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Accompany femoral vessels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"No motor function","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22178,"text":"The force of a tetanic contraction is greater than that of a twitch contraction due to which of the following?","explanation":"In a **tetanic contraction**, the muscle fiber is stimulated rapidly and continuously without allowing it to relax completely between stimuli. This sustained stimulation leads to repeated and **increased calcium release** from the sarcoplasmic reticulum. This allows for more cross-bridge formations between actin and myosin filaments, leading to a stronger and more sustained contraction.\r\n\r\nOn the other hand, in a twitch contraction, a single, brief stimulus results in a single, brief contraction. The calcium release is transient and not sustained.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nPotassium levels are not directly associated with the force of muscle contraction.\r\n\r\nAcetylcholine is involved in neuromuscular transmission but is not the primary factor influencing the force of contraction once the muscle is stimulated.\r\n\r\nWhile the duration of acetylcholine at the neuromuscular junction is important for neuromuscular transmission, it is not the primary determinant of the force of contraction.\r\n\r\nRapid action potentials are crucial for muscle contraction initiation but do not directly contribute to increased calcium release during sustained contraction.","reference":"(1) Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 89.\r\n\r\n(2) WEHMEIER N, Press OU. Oxford university press | online resource centre | multiple choice questions. Accessed December 30, 2023. http://global.oup.com/uk/orc/biosciences/sports/macdougall/student/mcqs/ch04/","responses":[{"text":"Longer duration of acetylcholine receptor at the neuromuscular junction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased calcium release","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased release of acetylcholine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rapid action potentials along T-tubules","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased potassium in extracellular fluid","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22179,"text":"In a scenario where there is insufficient ATP available during muscle fiber contraction, what is the immediate consequence?","explanation":"During muscle contraction, **cross-bridge cycling** between myosin and actin involves the binding and detachment of myosin heads to actin filaments, powered by the **hydrolysis of ATP**. This step is crucial for muscle relaxation as it allows the sarcomere to return to its original length.\r\n\r\nWithout enough ATP, the myosin heads cannot properly detach from actin. This leads to a situation where cross-bridges remain attached and the muscle stays contracted or, more accurately, in a state where it cannot fully relax. \r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nWhile the contraction is prolonged due to the inability to detach cross-bridges, it does not mean that the muscle fiber remains contracted indefinitely. Eventually, other cellular processes lead to relaxation.\r\n\r\nTroponin is a regulatory protein in the muscle that, along with tropomyosin, regulates the interaction between actin and myosin. ATP is not directly involved in troponin binding to myosin.\r\n\r\nThe release of calcium ions from the sarcoplasmic reticulum is an essential step in muscle contraction, but it is not directly a consequence of insufficient ATP.\r\n\r\nInsufficient ATP prevents the immediate detachment of cross-bridges, leading to a prolonged contraction rather than immediate relaxation.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 91.","responses":[{"text":"The muscle fiber remains contracted indefinitely","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Troponin binds to myosin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcium ions are released from sarcoplasmic reticulum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cross-bridges cannot detach, leading to prolong contraction","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"The muscle fiber relaxes immediately","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22180,"text":"Which of the following drugs are considered a directly acting muscle relaxant?","explanation":"**Dantrolene** is a **muscle relaxant** that acts **directly** on the skeletal muscle by interfering with the release of calcium ions from the sarcoplasmic reticulum. It is used to treat conditions associated with muscle spasticity and is often employed in the management of conditions such as spasticity due to neurological disorders or malignant hyperthermia.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nTizanidine acts on the spinal cord to reduce muscle activity, making it a centrally-acting muscle relaxant.\r\n\r\nDiazepam is a benzodiazepine that works on the central nervous system and is commonly used as a muscle relaxant, but it does not directly target muscle function.\r\n\r\nChlorzoxazone works by inhibiting pain signals in the spinal cord, making it another centrally-acting muscle relaxant.\r\n\r\nSuccinylcholine is a depolarizing neuromuscular blocking agent. It disrupts the communication between nerves and muscles, leading to temporary paralysis. However, it  is not typically referred to as a muscle relaxant in the context of treating spasticity or muscle conditions.","reference":"Katzung BG, Kruidering-Hall M, Trevor AJ. Katzung \u0026 Trevor’s Pharmacology Examination \u0026 Board Review. 13th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2021: 234.","responses":[{"text":"Diazepam","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chlorzoxazone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tizanidine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Succinylcholine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dantrolene","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":22181,"text":"ADHD is a condition that affects the development of the brain and has a lifelong impact. Research suggests that females with ADHD are more likely to go undiagnosed and untreated during childhood because their symptoms are often less noticeable and internalized compared to males. Which of the following is not a symptom found in females?","explanation":"While **disruptive behavior** is a common symptom in individuals with attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD), it may be more overtly noticeable in **males**. Females with ADHD often exhibit internalized symptoms, making their difficulties less disruptive in a classroom or social setting.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nBoth males and females with ADHD may experience forgetfulness as a symptom. It is related to difficulties in sustaining attention and organization.\r\n\r\nDaydreaming or inattentiveness is a shared symptom in both males and females with ADHD.\r\n\r\nDistractibility is a common symptom in both genders with ADHD, reflecting difficulties in filtering out irrelevant stimuli.\r\n\r\nFemales with ADHD may internalize their struggles, leading to feelings of shyness or social withdrawal.","reference":"Dow lecture slides: Locomotor, Behavioral Sciences, Topic name: ADHD hyperactivity disorders in adolescent.","responses":[{"text":"Forgetfulness","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Feeling shy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Distractibility","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Daydreaming","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Disruptiveness","correct":true,"visible":false}]}
]

export default a